{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"85c3c271-7a11-4ddf-afd7-103eac06755d","content":"You're on **MSTest 3.8.2** / .NET 9. Here's the recommended modern pattern:\n\n**Constructor injection** for `TestContext` + sync setup, and **`[TestInitialize]`** for async setup:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private MyService _service;\n\n    // Sync init + TestContext via constructor injection (MSTest v3+)\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        _service = new MyService();\n    }\n\n    // Async init\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        await _service.ConnectAsync();\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test\");\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_service);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **Constructor injection** of `TestContext` is the MSTest v3+ way (the older `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property still works but is legacy).\n- Put **synchronous** setup in the constructor.\n- Put **asynchronous** setup in an `async Task` method decorated with `[TestInitialize]`.\n- Both run per-test. For one-time class-level setup, use `[ClassInitialize]` (static) instead.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6006556e-c2b3-4706-a7fa-c0e3b297abdc","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9.0. In modern MSTest (v3+), the recommended approach is:\n\n1. **TestContext injection**: Use a constructor parameter or a public property. In MSTest v3+, the recommended way is constructor injection: `public MyTestClass(TestContext testContext)`.\n\n2. **Synchronous initialization**: Use `[TestInitialize]` method or the constructor.\n\n3. **Asynchronous initialization**: Use `[TestInitialize]` with an async method (returns `Task`).\n\nLet me give a concise, accurate answer.\n\nIn MSTest 3.x:\n\n\nConstructor injection is the preferred pattern for TestContext, and `[TestInitialize]` can handle both sync and async setup work. Class-level setup is available through `[ClassInitialize]` and `[ClassCleanup]` if needed.","outputTokens":625,"requestId":"0C00:38F59:40A001:4AFD12:69F00DC3"},"id":"60c53f8f-3110-44b8-97dc-320229170e90","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:30:56.202Z","parentId":"e9f4e802-c112-43a0-ae3e-06910d154e2f"}
